<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,638,587,688]" lastBlockId="7.[685,1173,194,534]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,280,587,608]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
PEL= 
<quantity box="[352,501,587,609]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.145" metricValueMax="4.86" metricValueMin="3.43" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="4.145" valueMax="4.86" valueMin="3.43">3.43–4.86 mm</quantity>
; PNW= 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.46" metricValueMax="4.3" metricValueMin="2.62" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="3.46" valueMax="4.3" valueMin="2.62">2.62– 4.30 mm</quantity>
. See diagnosis under 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Casey" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[457,601,614,635]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbilicatus">
<emphasis box="[457,601,614,635]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">M. umbilicatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for a diagnosis of this species. In more northern populations assigned to this species, especially in 
<collectingRegion box="[573,785,194,688]" country="Canada" name="British Columbia" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">British Columbia</collectingRegion>
, the lateral apical teeth of the median lobe tend to be much reduced, almost disappearing to leave a single median tooth in many individuals. In 
<collectingRegion box="[710,804,274,295]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">California</collectingRegion>
populations the lateral teeth are usually well developed, though smaller than the median one.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[685,1173,194,534]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,809,327,348]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Casey" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[822,1052,327,348]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="umbrosus">
<emphasis box="[822,1052,327,348]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Margarinotus umbrosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be a more generalist species than its close relatives, having been recorded from dung, carrion, and decaying vegetation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[685,1173,194,534]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,920,433,454]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Distribution (
<figureCitation box="[843,906,433,454]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[731,766,778,797]" captionTargetBox="[708,1193,183,754]" captionTargetId="figure-546@6.[707,1194,183,754]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 6. Map of known California localities for Margarinotus spp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4892942" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4892942/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
This species occurs along the Pacific coast from central 
<collectingRegion box="[962,1055,460,481]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">California</collectingRegion>
(Marin Co.) through 
<collectingRegion box="[768,935,486,507]" country="Canada" name="British Columbia" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">British Columbia</collectingRegion>
ranging eastward in the north to 
<collectingRegion box="[765,848,513,534]" country="United States of America" name="Montana" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Montana</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[894,966,513,534]" country="Canada" name="Alberta" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Alberta</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
